<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1913-10-17T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1913-10-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="1053" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1053">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/9462.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Chargé d’Affaires at
                                    San Salvador</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 331.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Legation</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">San Salvador</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1913-10-17">
                                    <hi rend="italic">October 17, 1913</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to the Department’s telegraphic
                            instruction of October 14, 7 p.m., I have the honor to report that the
                            Under Secretary of Foreign Affairs told me that his Government knew
                            nothing officially of recent events in Mexico as the Salvadoran Minister
                            accredited to that Republic was at present on leave in this city, and
                            that the Government of Salvador was astonished at the high-handed
                            actions of General Huerta. The present attitude of the Government of the
                            United States toward Mexico, he added, met with the approval of his
                            Government, which believed that it was for the ultimate good of the
                            Mexican people.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Thomas Hinckley</hi>.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>